Definition 4.3. A Grothendieck homotopy left Kan extension along $f$, $Hof_{!}:\mathcal{C}^{I}[\mathcal{W}^{-1}]\rightarrow\mathcal{C}^{J}[\mathcal{W% }^{-1}]$, is defined as the left adjoint of $f^{\ast}:\mathcal{C}^{J}[\mathcal{W}^{-1}]\rightarrow\mathcal{C}^{I}[\mathcal{% W}^{-1}]$ (if it exists). On the other hand, if there exists the left Kan extension $f_{!}:\mathcal{C}^{I}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}^{J}$, a Quillen homotopy left Kan extension along $f$ is defined as the absolute left derived functor $\mathbb{L}f_{!}:\mathcal{C}^{I}[\mathcal{W}^{-1}]\rightarrow\mathcal{C}^{J}[% \mathcal{W}^{-1}]$ of $f_{!}$ (if it exists).
Definition 5.3. A dg-functor $f:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ between two dg-categories $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ is a functor of enriched categories over $\mathrm{C}(k)$. That is, $\mathrm{Hom}(f):\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(x,y)\rightarrow\mathrm{Hom}_{% \mathcal{B}}(f(x),f(y))$ is a morphism of complexes compatible with composition. Note that $f$ induces in particular a functor $[f]:[\mathcal{A}]\rightarrow[\mathcal{B}]$.
Definition 5.2. A dg-category $\mathcal{A}$ is a category enriched over the category $\mathrm{C}(k)$ of complexes of $k$-modules, where $k$ is some fixed ring. More concretely, $\mathcal{A}$ consists of a class (or set) $Ob\mathcal{A}$ of objects, and a hom-object $\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(x,y)$ of $\mathrm{C}(k)$ for any two objects $x$ and $y$. In addition, there are morphisms of complexes (composition) $\tau_{x,y,z}:\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(x,y)\otimes_{k}\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{% A}}(y,z)\longrightarrow\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(x,z)$ subject to the usual associativity and unit axioms. From a dg-category $\mathcal{A}$ one can construct a usual category $[\mathcal{A}]$ with same objects as $\mathcal{A}$, and morphisms $\mathrm{Hom}_{[\mathcal{A}]}(x,y)=\mathrm{H}^{0}\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(x,y)$. Definition 5.3. A dg-functor $f:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ between two dg-categories $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ is a functor of enriched categories over $\mathrm{C}(k)$. That is, $\mathrm{Hom}(f):\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(x,y)\rightarrow\mathrm{Hom}_{% \mathcal{B}}(f(x),f(y))$ is a morphism of complexes compatible with composition. Note that $f$ induces in particular a functor $[f]:[\mathcal{A}]\rightarrow[\mathcal{B}]$. From the fact that $\mathrm{C}(k)$ is closed symmetric monoidal readily follows that the category $dgcat$ of dg-categories and dg-functors is again closed symmetric monoidal. Indeed, $\mathcal{A}\otimes\mathcal{B}$ has $Ob\mathcal{A}\times Ob\mathcal{B}$ as objects, and $\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(-,-)\otimes_{k}\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}(-,-)$ as morphisms.
Definition 4.1. A Grothendieck homotopy colimit is defined as the left adjoint $\mathrm{hocolim}_{I}:\mathcal{C}^{I}[\mathcal{W}^{-1}]\rightarrow\mathcal{C}[% \mathcal{W}^{-1}]$ of the localized constant diagram functor $c_{I}:\mathcal{C}[\mathcal{W}^{-1}]\rightarrow\mathcal{C}^{I}[\mathcal{W}^{-1}]$ (if it exists). On the other hand, if there exists the colimit $\mathrm{colim}_{I}:\mathcal{C}^{I}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$, a Quillen homotopy colimit is defined as the absolute left derived functor $\mathbb{L}\mathrm{colim}_{I}:\mathcal{C}^{I}[\mathcal{W}^{-1}]\rightarrow% \mathcal{C}[\mathcal{W}^{-1}]$ of the colimit $\mathrm{colim}_{I}$ (if it exists).
Definition 1. Let $({\rm W,C,F})$ be a model structure on a category M. An $\ell\ell$-extension (or, extension of type $\ell\ell$) of $({\rm W,C,F})$ is a model structure $({\rm W}^{\mathcal{G}},{\rm C}^{\mathcal{G}},{\rm F}^{\mathcal{G}})$ on M such that ${\rm W}\subset{\rm W}^{\mathcal{G}}$, ${\rm C}^{\mathcal{G}}\subseteq{\rm C}$ and ${\rm F}^{\mathcal{G}}\subseteq{\rm F}$.
Definition 2. Let $f:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ be a morphism in $\mathcal{V}$-Cat. 1. The morphism $f$ is a weak equivalence if $f$ is locally a weak equivalence of $\mathcal{V}$ and $[f]_{\mathcal{V}}:[\mathcal{A}]_{\mathcal{V}}\rightarrow[\mathcal{B}]_{% \mathcal{V}}$ is essentially surjective. 2. The morphism $f$ is a fibration if $(a)$ $f$ is locally a fibration of $\mathcal{V}$, and $(b)$ for any $x\in Ob(\mathcal{A})$, and any isomorphism $v:y^{\prime}\rightarrow[f]_{\mathcal{V}}(x)$ in $[\mathcal{B}]_{\mathcal{V}}$, there exists an isomorphism $u:x^{\prime}\rightarrow x$ in $[\mathcal{A}]_{\mathcal{V}}$ such that $[f]_{\mathcal{V}}(u)=v$. 3. The morphism $f$ is called a cofibration if it has the left lifting property with respect to the fibrations which are weak equivalences.
Definition 44 A distance matrix homomorphism $h:\Phi\rightarrow\Gamma$ where $\Phi:A\looparrowright B$ and $\Gamma:C\looparrowright D$, is a pair of contractions $h=\left<h_{0}:A\rightarrow C,h_{1}:B\rightarrow D\right>$ such that • ${\rm\Omega}h_{0}\,;\Gamma=\Phi\,;{\rm\Omega}h_{1}$, • $h_{0}$ preserves any suprema that may exist in $A$, • $h_{1}$ preserves any infima that may exist in $B$. Let ${\sf MMat}$ denote the category of distance space matrices and matrix morphisms.
Definition 24 The cones in a distance space $A$ are the sequences in $\left(\overrightarrow{A}\right)_{\nabla_{\#}{\rm\Delta}^{\#}}$ and $\left(\overleftarrow{A}\right)_{{\rm\Delta}^{\#}\nabla_{\#}}$. A cut in $A$ is a pair of cones $\gamma=<\overrightarrow{\gamma},\overleftarrow{\gamma}>\in\left(% \overrightarrow{A}\right)_{\nabla_{\#}{\rm\Delta}^{\#}}\times\left(% \overleftarrow{A}\right)_{{\rm\Delta}^{\#}\nabla_{\#}}$ such that $\overrightarrow{\gamma}=\nabla_{\#}\overleftarrow{\gamma}$. The set of cuts is denoted by $\overleftrightarrow{A}$.
Definition 9 The weighted supremum $\textstyle\coprod_{\overrightarrow{\varrho}}k$ of the right diagram $<k,{\overrightarrow{\varrho}}^{o}>:K\rightarrow A\times{[0,\infty]}^{o}$ and the weighted infimum $\textstyle\prod_{\overleftarrow{\lambda}}k$ of the left diagram $<k,\overleftarrow{\lambda}>:K\rightarrow A\times[0,\infty]$ are the elements of $A$ that satisfy for every $x,y\in A$ $\displaystyle d_{A}\left({\textstyle\coprod_{\overrightarrow{\varrho}}k},{y}\right)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\bigvee_{x\in K}x\overrightarrow{\varrho}\multimap d_{A}\left({kx% },{y}\right)$ $\displaystyle d_{A}\left({x},{\textstyle\prod_{\overleftarrow{\lambda}}k}\right)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\bigvee_{y\in K}\overleftarrow{\lambda}y\multimap d_{A}\left({x},% {k{y}}\right)$
Definition 32 A matrix $\Phi:A\looparrowright B$ is embedding if $\Phi\,;{\Phi}^{\ddagger}={\rm Id}_{A}$; and a projection if ${\Phi}^{\ddagger}\,;\Phi={\rm Id}_{B}$.
Definition 1 A distance space is a set $A$ with a metric $d_{A}:A\times A\rightarrow[0,\infty]$ which is • reflexive: $d\left({x},{x}\right)=0$, • transitive: $d\left({x},{y}\right)+d\left({y},{z}\right)\ \geq\ d\left({x},{z}\right)$, and • antisymmetric: $d\left({x},{y}\right)=0=d\left({y},{x}\right)\ \Longrightarrow\ x=y$ A contraction between the distance spaces $A$ and $B$ is a function $f:A\rightarrow B$ such that for all $x,y\in A$ holds $d_{A}\left({x},{y}\right)\geq d_{B}\left({fx},{fy}\right)$. The category of distance spaces and contractions is denoted ${\sf Dist}$.
Definition 37 $\Lbag{\Phi}\Rbag$ is called the nucleus of the matrix $\Phi$. Its elements are the $\Phi$-cuts.
Definition 20 A map $g$ from a distance space $A$ to a distance space $B$ is an embedding if it preserves the distance, i.e. satisfies $d_{A}\left({x},{y}\right)=d_{B}\left({gx},{gy}\right)$ for all $x,y\in A$. An adjoint of an embedding is called a projection. An adjunction $p^{\ast}:A\rightleftarrows B:e_{\ast}$ of a left projection and right adjoint, as in Prop. 19(a-b), is called a reflection. An adjunction $e^{\ast}:A\rightleftarrows B:p_{\ast}$ of a left embedding and right projection, as in Prop. 19(c-d), is called a coreflection.
Definition 7 The supremum $\textstyle\coprod\overrightarrow{\varrho}$ of the right sequence $\overrightarrow{\varrho}$ and the infimum $\textstyle\prod\overleftarrow{\lambda}$ of the left sequence $\overleftarrow{\lambda}$ are the elements of $A$ that satisfy for every $x,y\in A$ $\displaystyle d_{A}\left({\textstyle\coprod\overrightarrow{\varrho}},{y}\right)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\bigvee_{x\in A}x\overrightarrow{\varrho}\multimap d_{A}\left({x}% ,{y}\right)$ $\displaystyle d_{A}\left({x},{\textstyle\prod\overleftarrow{\lambda}}\right)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\bigvee_{y\in A}\overleftarrow{\lambda}y\multimap d_{A}\left({x},% {y}\right)$ Suprema and infima constitute the limits of a distance space. The distance space $A$ is right (resp. left) complete if every right (resp. left) sequence has a limit. The suprema and the infima thus yield the operations $\textstyle\coprod:\ \ \overrightarrow{A}\rightarrow A\qquad\mbox{and}\qquad% \textstyle\prod:\ \ \overleftarrow{A}\rightarrow A$
Definition 30 Transposing the indices yields the transposed matrix: ${tensy\vbox{\hbox spread 0.0pt{\hbox{\kern 8.399872pt\hbox{$\displaystyle% \penalty 1\Phi\ :\ A\looparrowright B\ :\ {x}{\Phi}{y}$}}}\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.% 0pt\vrule height 0.25pt depth 0.25pt width 104.298714pt\hbox{}}}\hbox{\kern 0.% 0pt\hbox{$\displaystyle{\Phi}^{o}\ :\ {B}^{o}\looparrowright{A}^{o}\ :\ {y}{{% \Phi}^{o}}{x}$}}}}$ The dual ${\Phi}^{\ddagger}:B\looparrowright A$ of a matrix $\Phi:A\looparrowright B$ has the entries ${tensy\vbox{\hbox spread 0.0pt{\hbox{\kern 25.69854pt\hbox{$\displaystyle% \penalty 1\Phi\ :\ A\looparrowright B\ :\ {x}{\Phi}{y}\hskip 140.0pt$}}}\hbox{% \hbox{\kern 0.0pt\vrule height 0.25pt depth 0.25pt width 278.896049pt\hbox{}}}% \hbox{\kern 0.0pt\hbox{$\displaystyle{\Phi}^{\ddagger}\ :\ B\looparrowright A% \ :\ {y}{{\Phi}^{\ddagger}}{x}=\bigvee_{\begin{subarray}{c}u\in A\\ v\in B\end{subarray}}{u}{\Phi}{v}\multimap\left(d_{A}\left({u},{x}\right)+d_{B% }\left({y},{v}\right)\right)$}}}}$ A matrix $\Phi:A\looparrowright B$ where $\Phi^{{\ddagger}{\ddagger}}=\Phi$ is called a suspension.
Definition 10 A contraction $f:A\rightarrow B$ preserves • weighted suprema if $f\left(\textstyle\coprod_{\overrightarrow{\varrho}}k\right)\ =\ \textstyle% \coprod_{\overrightarrow{\varrho}}(f\circ k)$, and • weighted infima if $f\left(\textstyle\prod_{\overleftarrow{\lambda}}k\right)\ =\ \textstyle\prod_{% \overleftarrow{\lambda}}(f\circ k)$.
Definition 4 In a distance space $A$, a (canonical) sequence is defined to be a contraction into $[0,\infty]$. More precisely, we define that • a left sequence is a covariant contraction $\overleftarrow{\lambda}:A\rightarrow[0,\infty]$ – we write its value at $x\in A$ as $\overleftarrow{\lambda}x$ • a right sequence is a contravariant contraction $\overrightarrow{\varrho}:{A}^{o}\rightarrow[0,\infty]$ – we write its value at $x\in A$ as $x\overrightarrow{\varrho}$. Each of the sets of sequences $\overleftarrow{A}={\left([0,\infty]^{A}\right)}^{o}\qquad\mbox{ and}\qquad% \overrightarrow{A}=[0,\infty]^{\left({A}^{o}\right)}$ forms a distance space, with the metrics $d_{\overleftarrow{A}}\left({\overleftarrow{\lambda}},{\overleftarrow{\theta}}% \right)=\bigvee_{x\in A}\overleftarrow{\theta}x\multimap\overleftarrow{\lambda% }x\qquad\mbox{ and}\qquad d_{\overrightarrow{A}}\left({\overrightarrow{\varrho% }},{\overrightarrow{\mu}}\right)=\bigvee_{x\in A}x\overrightarrow{\varrho}% \multimap x\overrightarrow{\mu}$
Definition 8 For distance spaces $A$ and $K$ we define • left diagrams as pairs of contractions $\left<k:K\rightarrow A,\overleftarrow{\lambda}:K\rightarrow[0,\infty]\right>$ • right diagrams as pairs of contractions $\left<k:K\rightarrow A,\overrightarrow{\varrho}:{K}^{o}\rightarrow[0,\infty]\right>$
Definition 21 A nucleus of the adjunction $f^{\ast}:A\rightleftarrows B:f_{\ast}$ consists of a distance space $\Lbag{f}\Rbag$ together with • embeddings $A\stackrel{{\scriptstyle e_{\ast}}}{{\hookleftarrow}}\Lbag{f}\Rbag\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle e^{\ast}}}{{\hookrightarrow}}B$ • projections $A\stackrel{{\scriptstyle p^{\ast}}}{{\twoheadrightarrow}}\Lbag{f}\Rbag% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle p_{\ast}}}{{\twoheadleftarrow}}B$ such that $f^{\ast}=e^{\ast}p^{\ast}$ and $f_{\ast}=e_{\ast}p_{\ast}$.
Definition 5 An element $u$ of a distance space $A$ is an upper bound of a right sequence $\overrightarrow{\varrho}$ in $A$ if for all $x\in A$ holds $\displaystyle x\overrightarrow{\varrho}$ $\displaystyle\geq$ $\displaystyle d_{A}\left({x},{u}\right)$ An element $\ell$ of a distance space $A$ is a lower bound of a left sequence $\overleftarrow{\lambda}$ in $A$ if for all $y\in A$ holds $\displaystyle\overleftarrow{\lambda}y$ $\displaystyle\geq$ $\displaystyle d_{A}\left({\ell},{y}\right)$
Definition 16 A right adjoint is a contraction satisfying (a-c) of Prop. 15; a left adjoint satisfies (d-f). A (distance) adjunction between the distance spaces $A$ and $B$ is a pair of contractions $f^{\ast}:A\rightleftarrows B:f_{\ast}$ related as in (b-c) and (e-f).
Definition 33 A decomposition of a matrix $\Phi:A\looparrowright B$ consists of a distance space $D$, with • projection matrix $P:A\looparrowright D$, i.e. $d_{D}\left({d},{d^{\prime}}\right)=\bigwedge_{x\in A}{d}{{P}^{\ddagger}}{x}+{x% }{P}{d^{\prime}}$, • embedding matrix $E:D\looparrowright B$, i.e. $d_{D}\left({d},{d^{\prime}}\right)=\bigwedge_{y\in B}{d}{E}{y}+{y}{{E}^{% \ddagger}}{d^{\prime}}$, such that $\Phi=P\,;E$, i.e. ${x}{\Phi}{y}=\bigwedge_{d\in D}{x}{P}{d}+{d}{E}{y}$.
Definition 45 A matrix $\Phi:A\looparrowright B$ is complete if $A$ has suprema and $B$ infima1By Corollary 28, both $A$ and $B$ are thus complete, and $\Phi:{A}^{o}\times B\rightarrow[0,\infty]$ preserves the infima. Let ${\sf CMat}$ denote the category of complete matrices and matrix homomorphisms.
Definition 29 A distance matrix $\Phi$ from distance space $A$ to distance space $B$ is a sequence $\Phi:{A}^{o}\times B\rightarrow[0,\infty]$. We denote it by $\Phi:A\looparrowright B$, and the value of $\Phi$ at $x\in A$ and $y\in B$ is written ${x}{\Phi}{y}$. The matrix composition of $\Phi:A\looparrowright B$ and $\Psi:B\looparrowright C$ is defined $\displaystyle{x}{(\Phi\,;\Psi)}{z}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\bigwedge_{y\in B}{x}{\Phi}{y}+{y}{\Psi}{z}$ With this composition and the identities ${\rm Id}_{A}:A\looparrowright A$ where $x({\rm Id}_{A})x^{\prime}\ =\ d_{A}\left({x},{x^{\prime}}\right)$, distance spaces and distance space matrices form the category ${\sf Matr}$.
Definition 3.2. A morphism $f:\hom_{A}(a,b)$ is an isomorphism if there is a morphism $g:\hom_{A}(b,a)$ such that $g\circ f=1_{a}$ and $f\circ g=1_{b}$. We write $a\cong b$ for the type of such isomorphisms.
Definition 6.2. We say a functor $F:A\to B$ is faithful if for all $a,b:A$, the function $F_{a,b}:\hom_{A}(a,b)\to\hom_{B}(Fa,Fb)$ is injective, and full if for all $a,b:A$ this function is surjective. If it is both (hence each $F_{a,b}$ is an equivalence) we say $F$ is fully faithful.
Definition 7.1. For a precategory $A$, its opposite $A^{\textrm{op}}$ is a precategory with the same type of objects, with $\hom_{A^{\textrm{op}}}(a,b)\coloneqq\hom_{A}(b,a)$, and with identities and composition inherited from $A$.
Definition 4.4. For functors $F:A\to B$ and $G:B\to C$, their composite $G\circ F:A\to C$ is given by • The composite $(G_{0}\circ F_{0}):A_{0}\to C_{0}$ • For each $a,b:A$, the composite $(G_{Fa,Fb}\circ F_{a,b}):\hom_{A}(a,b)\to\hom_{C}(GFa,GFb).$ It is easy to check the axioms.
Definition 7.3. A functor $F:\underline{\mathsf{Set}}^{A^{\textrm{op}}}$ is said to be representable if there exists $a:A$ and an isomorphism $\mathbf{y}a\cong F$.
Definition 5.1. A functor $F:A\to B$ is a left adjoint if there exists • A functor $G:B\to A$. • A natural transformation $\eta:1_{A}\to GF$. • A natural transformation $\epsilon:FG\to 1_{B}$. • $(\epsilon F)(F\eta)=1_{F}$. • $(G\epsilon)(\eta G)=1_{G}$.
Definition 4.2. For functors $F,G:A\to B$, a natural transformation $\gamma:F\to G$ consists of (i) For each $a:A$, a morphism $\gamma_{a}:\hom_{B}(Fa,Ga)$. (ii) For each $a,b:A$ and $f:\hom_{A}(a,b)$, we have $Gf\circ\gamma_{a}=\gamma_{b}\circ Ff$.
Definition 6.4. A functor $F:A\to B$ is essentially surjective if for all $b:B$, there merely exists an $a:A$ such that $Fa\cong b$. We say $F$ is a weak equivalence if it is fully faithful and essentially surjective.
Definition 3.3. A category is a precategory such that for all $a,b:A$, the function $\mathsf{idtoiso}_{a,b}$ from Lemma 3.2 is an equivalence.
Definition 4.5. For functors $F:A\to B$ and $G,H:B\to C$ and a natural transformation $\gamma:G\to H$, the composite $(\gamma F):GF\to HF$ is given by • For each $a:A$, the component $\gamma_{Fa}$. Naturality is easy to check. Similarly, for $\gamma$ as above and $K:C\to D$, the composite $(K\gamma):KG\to KH$ is given by • For each $b:B$, the component $K(\gamma_{b})$.
Definition 7.2. For precategories $A$ and $B$, their product $A\times B$ is a precategory with $(A\times B)_{0}\coloneqq A_{0}\times B_{0}$ and $\hom_{A\times B}((a,b),(a^{\prime},b^{\prime}))\coloneqq\hom_{A}(a,a^{\prime})% \times\hom_{B}(b,b^{\prime}).$ Identities are defined by $1_{(a,b)}\coloneqq(1_{a},1_{b})$ and composition by $(g,g^{\prime})(f,f^{\prime})\coloneqq((gf),(g^{\prime}f^{\prime}))$.
Definition 4.1. Let $A$ and $B$ be precategories. A functor $F:A\to B$ consists of (i) A function $F_{0}:A_{0}\to B_{0}$, generally also denoted $F$. (ii) For each $a,b:A$, a function $F_{a,b}:\hom_{A}(a,b)\to\hom_{B}(Fa,Fb)$, generally also denoted $F$. (iii) For each $a:A$, we have $F(1_{a})=1_{Fa}$. (iv) For each $a,b,c:A$ and $f:\hom_{A}(a,b)$ and $g:\hom_{B}(b,c)$, we have $F(g\circ f)=Fg\circ Ff.$
Definition 6.3. We say a functor $F:A\to B$ is split essentially surjective if for all $b:B$ there exists an $a:A$ such that $Fa\cong b$.
Definition 3.1. A precategory $A$ consists of the following. (i) A type $A_{0}$ of objects. We write $a:A$ for $a:A_{0}$. (ii) For each $a,b:A$, a set $\hom_{A}(a,b)$ of arrows or morphisms. (iii) For each $a:A$, a morphism $1_{a}:\hom_{A}(a,a)$. (iv) For each $a,b,c:A$, a function $\hom_{A}(b,c)\to\hom_{A}(a,b)\to\hom_{A}(a,c)$ denoted infix by $g\mapsto f\mapsto g\circ f$, or sometimes simply by $gf$. (v) For each $a,b:A$ and $f:\hom_{A}(a,b)$, we have $f=1_{b}\circ f$ and $f=f\circ 1_{a}$. (vi) For each $a,b,c,d:A$ and $f:\hom_{A}(a,b)$, $g:\hom_{A}(b,c)$, $h:\hom_{A}(c,d)$, we have $h\circ(g\circ f)=(h\circ g)\circ f$.
Definition 4.3. For precategories $A,B$, there is a precategory $B^{A}$ defined by • $(B^{A})_{0}$ is the type of functors from $A$ to $B$. • $\hom_{B^{A}}(F,G)$ is the type of natural transformations from $F$ to $G$.
Definition 6.5. A functor $F:A\to B$ is an isomorphism of (pre)categories if $F$ is fully faithful and $F_{0}:A_{0}\to B_{0}$ is an equivalence of types.
Definition 6.1. A functor $F:A\to B$ is an equivalence of (pre)categories if it is a left adjoint for which $\eta$ and $\epsilon$ are isomorphisms. We write $A\simeq B$ for the type of equivalences of categories from $A$ to $B$.
Definition 2.1. We will call this left adjoint the standardization functor and denote it by $\Delta_{\xi}$. We will often omit $\xi$ from the notation. For $\lambda\in\Lambda$ let $\Delta(\lambda)$ (resp., $\bar{\Delta}(\lambda)$) denote the object $\Delta_{\varrho(\lambda)}(P_{\xi}(\lambda))$ (resp., $\Delta_{\varrho(\lambda)}(L_{\xi}(\lambda))$). The objects $\Delta(\lambda),\bar{\Delta}(\lambda)$ will be called standard and proper standard. We call the category $\mathcal{C}$ equipped with a filtration $\mathcal{C}_{\leqslant\xi}$ (such that $\Delta_{\xi}$ is an exact functor) a standardly stratified category if there is an epimorphism $P(\lambda)\twoheadrightarrow\Delta(\lambda)$ whose kernel admits a filtration by objects $\Delta(\mu)$ with $\mu>\lambda$.
Definition 2.3. Define the costandard object $\nabla(\lambda)$ as the maximal subobject of $I(\lambda)$ whose simple constituents are of the form $L(\mu)$ with $\mu\leqslant\lambda$. Also define the proper costandard object $\bar{\nabla}(\lambda)$ as the maximal subobject of $I(\lambda)$ such that the simple subquotients of $\bar{\nabla}(\lambda)/L(\lambda)$ are of the form $L(\mu)$ with $\mu<\lambda$. Let $\mathcal{C}^{\nabla}$ (resp., $\mathcal{C}^{\bar{\nabla}}$) denote the full subcategories of $\mathcal{C}$ consisting of all objects admitting a filtration whose successive quotients are costandard (resp., proper costandard) objects.
Definition 3.13. Let $\mathcal{C}(\mathbf{m})$ be the the sum of blocks of $\mathcal{O}$ spanned by $\Delta(\lambda)$ with $\lambda_{i}\in\{1,\ldots,m\}$.
Definition 3.1. A strongly equivariant functor between two categories $\mathcal{C}_{1},\mathcal{C}_{2}$ with categorical $\mathfrak{g}$-actions is • a functor $\eta\colon\mathcal{C}_{1}\to\mathcal{C}_{2}$ together with • isomorphisms of functors $E\eta\cong\eta E$ which commute with the $R$-actions on $E^{k}\eta\cong\eta E^{k}$. If we think of a categorical $\mathfrak{g}$-action as a representation of the 2-category $\mathfrak{U}$ in the strong 2-category of $\mathbb{K}$-linear categories, this is the usual notion of natural transformation between representations of a 2-category. We call such a functor a strongly equivariant equivalence if $\eta$ is an equivalence.
Definition 2.1. (i) Let $\mathscr{M}$ be a symmetric monoidal category with a class $T$ of morphisms containing all isomorphisms in $\mathscr{M}$. Such $\mathscr{M}$ is called a monoidal category with weak equivalences and the morphisms in $T$ are called weak equivalences if the monoidal product of two morphisms in $T$ is again a morphism in $T$. (ii) A Segal-Leinster monoid in a category $\mathscr{M}$ with weak equivalences is a colax-monoidal functor $A\colon\Delta_{f}^{\mathrm{opp}}\to\mathscr{M}$ whose colax maps $\beta_{m,n}\colon A_{m+n}\to A_{m}\otimes A_{n}$ and $\alpha\colon A([0])\to\underline{e}$ are weak equivalences (here $e$ is the unit in $\mathscr{M}$, and $\underline{e}$ is a monoid in $\mathscr{M}$ with single object $e$, and with morphisms $\mathrm{Hom}(e,e)$), (iii) A Segal-Leinster pre-monoid in $\mathscr{M}$ is the same data with skipping the condition that the colax maps are weak equivalences.
Definition 2.2. Let $A$ be a honest monoid in a monoidal category $\mathscr{M}$. The corresponding Segal-Leinster monoid $A^{\mathrm{SL}}$ is defined as $A_{n}^{\mathrm{SL}}=A\otimes A\otimes\dots\otimes A\text{\ \ \ ($n$ factors) % for $n\geq 1$},\ \ A_{0}=e$ where $e$ is the unit object in $\mathscr{M}$. Equation 2.2 defines a functor $A^{\mathrm{SL}}\colon\Delta^{\mathrm{opp}}_{f}\to\mathscr{M}$. The boundary maps $\delta_{i}\colon A_{n}^{\mathrm{SL}}\to A_{n-1}^{\mathrm{SL}}$ are defined as the identity elsewhere the $i$th and $(i+1)$st factors where it is equal to the product in $A$, $m\colon A\otimes A\to A$. The degeneracy maps $\epsilon_{i}\colon A_{n}^{\mathrm{SL}}\to A_{n+1}^{\mathrm{SL}}$ put the unit $e$ to the $i$th position, $1\leq i\leq n+1$. This functor has the natural colax-monoidal structure, with $\beta_{mn}\colon A_{m+n}^{\mathrm{SL}}\to A_{m}^{\mathrm{SL}}\otimes A_{n}^{% \mathrm{SL}}$ and $\alpha\colon A_{0}\to e$ the identity maps.
Definition 2.5. A Leinster $n$-algebra $A$ is an $n$-iterated Segal-Leinster monoid $(\Delta^{\mathrm{opp}}_{f})^{\times n}\to\mathscr{V}ect^{\>\raisebox{3.0pt}{% \text{\circle*{1.5}}}},\ \ \ [i_{1}]\times[i_{2}]\times\dots\times[i_{n}]% \mapsto A_{i_{1}i_{2}\dots i_{n}}$ which is an iterated colax-monoidal functor with weak equivalence colax-maps, with $A_{11\dots 1}=A$ Here we set $\mathscr{L}(0)=\mathscr{V}ect^{\>\raisebox{3.0pt}{\text{\circle*{1.5}}}}(k)$.
Definition 5.2. Let $\mathscr{A}$ be an abelian $k$-linear category, with a weakly compatible $n$-fold monoidal structure on it. We say that the $n$-fold monoidal structure is non-degenerate if for any four objects $X,Y,Z,W$ in $\mathscr{A}_{0}^{\mathrm{dg}}$, and for any $1\leq i<j\leq n$, the $(i,j)$-th Eckmann-Hilton map $\eta_{ij}\colon(X\otimes_{j}Y)\otimes_{i}(Z\otimes_{j}W)\to(X\otimes_{i}Z)% \otimes_{j}(Y\otimes_{i}W)$ becomes an isomorphism in the homotopy category $H^{0}(\mathscr{A}_{0}^{\mathrm{dg}})$.
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathscr{A}$ be an abelian category, with a monoidal structure $(\otimes,e)$ on it. Denote by $\mathscr{A}^{\mathrm{dg}}$ the dg category of bounded from above complexes in $\mathscr{A}$, and let $\mathscr{I}\subset\mathscr{A}^{\mathrm{dg}}$ be the full dg subcategory of acyclic objects. Consider the full additive subcategory $\mathscr{A}_{0}\subset\mathscr{A}$ where $X\in\mathscr{A}_{0}$ iff $X\otimes I$ and $I\otimes X$ are acyclic, for any acyclic $I\in\mathscr{I}$. Denote by $\mathscr{A}_{0}^{\mathrm{dg}}\subset\mathscr{A}^{\mathrm{dg}}$ the full dg subcategory of bounded from above complexes in $\mathscr{A}_{0}$. We say that the exact and the monoidal structures in $\mathscr{A}$ are weakly compatible if the natural imbedding $\mathscr{A}_{0}^{\mathrm{dg}}\hookrightarrow\mathscr{A}^{\mathrm{dg}}$ is a quasi-equivalence of dg categories.
